@B - I think you're misconstruing Barry's comment. 

He is posting a puzzle from 1942, back when those who whine about "trivia" claim there was some sort of "golden age" of trivia-free puzzle, precisely to show how much of what the whiners dismiss as "trivia"* has always been a part of the puzzles. 

* Frankly, almost all entries of all crosswords could be considered trivia. The only common exceptions are themers that would make nonsense outside of the puzzle, without a revealer.  As a regular at the local pub trivia nights, I resent that "trivia" is used to disparage entries that, frankly, are just too difficult for a small but annoying subset of the commentariat. I very much doubt that they would do well at any pub trivia contests. I hope we don't dumb the puzzles down to accommodate their incessant ululations about clues that are beyond their ken.

