Most publications that accept crosswords on spec (as it were) require that grids be symmetrical. This goes way back, at least for the NYT. Asymmetrical grids in those publications are rare, but if the theme justifies the asymmetry, it‚Äôs allowed. 

I don‚Äôt really know why symmetry is usually a requirement. A symmetrical grid does make it easier for solvers to identify theme answers. But a lot of good theme ideas have died because the constructor couldn‚Äôt find a symmetrical set of theme answers.
